  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Circumstantial Accusative (الحال)",
      "titleArabic": "الحال",
      "content": [
        "The حال (circumstantial accusative) describes the state or condition of the subject or object when the action takes place. It answers the question 'How?' or 'In what state?'",
        "The حال is always indefinite (نكرة) and in the accusative case (منصوب). It typically comes from active participles."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Always منصوب (accusative case)",
        "Always نكرة (indefinite) - no ال",
        "Describes the state of the subject or object during the action",
        "Usually derived from active participles (اسم الفاعل)",
        "Must agree in gender and number with صاحب الحال"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جَاءَ مَاشِيًا", "english": "He came walking" },
        { "arabic": "خَرَجَتْ مُسْرِعَةً", "english": "She went out hurrying" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهُ جَالِسًا", "english": "I saw him sitting" },
        { "arabic": "دَخَلَ مُبْتَسِمًا", "english": "He entered smiling" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "صاحب الحال (Owner of the State)",
      "titleArabic": "صاحب الحال",
      "content": [
        "The صاحب الحال is the noun that the حال describes. It can be the subject (فاعل) or object (مفعول به) of the sentence."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "صاحب الحال must be معرفة (definite)",
        "Subject as صاحب الحال: جَاءَ الطَّالِبُ مُسْرِعًا",
        "Object as صاحب الحال: رَأَيْتُ الطَّالِبَ جَالِسًا",
        "الحال agrees with صاحب الحال in gender and number"
      ]
    }
  ],
